  "discussion": "The trial court erred in overruling appellant’s Batson challenge to the State’s peremptory dismissal of the only African-American juror on the panel. The record reveals that both appellant and juror No. 5 are African-American. The trial court recognized this fact, requested the state to provide race neutral reasons for exercising its peremptory challenge, and proceeded to determine whether appellant’s Batson challenge was meritorious. The state asserted that it was excusing juror No. 5 because of her age and apparent lack of education. Age and education are race neutral elements and are not inherently discriminatory. The trial court found that the state had articulated a race neutral explanation for striking juror No. 5. However, the court’s reliance on the absence of a pattern of peremptory strikes against African-Americans was clearly erroneous. The trial court also found that the prosecutor exercised his peremptory challenge in good faith and without an untoward basis. However, the court’s finding concerning appellant’s proof of discrimination was in error. The record demonstrates that the prosecutor’s race-neutral reasons for striking juror No. 5 were merely pretexts used by the state to justify its otherwise discriminatory peremptory challenge of juror No. 5. The trial court clearly erred when it found that appellant did not meet his burden in proving a Batson violation."
}
