icated that appellant’s vehicle was at several banks when attempts were made to pass fraudulent checks. Det. Witalis also averred that the vehicle visited a check cashing business — the same check cashing business that employed Bohanon — prior to visiting the various financial institutions where fraudulent checks were passed. Regardless, at the suppression hearing, appellant argued in his opening statement that the GPS warrant affidavits were deficient, but then failed to pursue the issue further at the suppression hearing. All the evidence adduced was in relation to the court order issued by a municipal court judge for phone records, not the GPS warrants that were issued by a common pleas court judge. Appellant adduced testimony that detectives failed to disclose facts about D.H. — she had a history of mental illness including recent hospitalization, and she lied to police about her address — but that was in the context of the court order to obtain cell phone records. As this court recognized in Perry, it is the defendant’s burden to demonstrate a material misstatement or omission in a search warrant affidavit under Franks. Perry, 8th Dist. Cuyahoga No. 97572, 2012-Ohio-4273, ¶ 15. Appellant failed to do so at the suppression hearing. Therefore, appellant’s first assignment of error is overruled."
